Cardiovascular Health: A Comprehensive Analysis of Cardiovascular Data

Steven Raimondo

2024-10-01


1 Introduction

1.1 Background

The primary goal of this comprehensive analysis of cardiovascular data is to identify significant predictors of cardiovascular health and possible associated cardiovascular disease presence. Additionally, we looked at whether these explanatory variables were a good set of predictors for the patients weight. The rise of better data management via complex interwoven computer networks allows us to better examine cardiovascular and other health related issues by saving countless hours of time and effort compiling, managing, and cleaning the data by more efficient means. The result of this innovation is we are able to look more closely at diseases and associated possible confounding factors that will lend insight into the significant factors that result in such illnesses and conditions. The aim of this analysis is to do such activity as our data is robust and extensive which can help accurately uncover insights into cardiovascular health.

The factors that contribute to cardiovascular disease lets us better understand insights into how demographic, lifestyle, and health-related factors can influence cardiovascular outcomes. Our goal and any researchers goal is and should be identifying ways and risks to help mitigate the prevalence of cardiovascular diseases in this case looking at possible explanatory variables. Well employ both linear and logistic regression model building methods to help ascertain different answers to questions of interest.

1.1.1 Questions to be Addressed

  1. What variables are significant and how their relationships affect helping to predict a patients Weight utilizing linear regression?

  2. What demographic and lifestyle factors (explanatory variables) significantly contribute to the presence of cardiovascular disease using logistic regression for our response variable CardioDisease?

Some additional questions of interest will surround the relationships between the predictor variables will include the following but not limited to

1) What is the relationship between Weight and CardioDisease?
  1. Determine the most influential predictor variables for Weight and CardioDisease

1.2 Cardio Data

There are 16 variables and 68,205 observations in the dataset that was aggregated from multiple sources including: (Janosi et al., 1989) and (Yasserh, 2021) utilizing patient information from the Cleveland health database while patient identifying information has been removed to ensure patient privacy. The following list includes the variable names, descriptions, type of variable, and outputs:

ID: Unique identifier for each patient (Integer)

Age: Age of the patient in days (Integer)

Height: Height of the patient in centimeters (Integer)

Weight: Weight of the patient in kilograms (Numeric)

Systolic_BP: Systolic blood pressure (Integer)

Diastolic_BP: Diastolic blood pressure (Integer)

BMI: Body Mass Index, calculated from weight and height (Numeric)

Age_Years: Age of the patient in years, derived from age (Numeric)

Gender: Gender of the patient (Categorical: Female, Male)

Cholesterol: Cholesterol levels (Categorical: Normal, Above Normal, High)

Glucose: Glucose levels (Categorical: Normal, Above Normal, High)

Smoke: Smoking status (Categorical: Non-smoker, Smoker)

Alcohol: Alcohol intake (Categorical: No alcohol, Consumes alcohol)

Active: Physical activity status (Categorical: Not Active, Active)

CardioDisease: Presence of cardiovascular disease (Categorical: No, Yes)

Bp_Category: Blood pressure category based on systolic and diastolic blood pressure values (Categorical: Normal, Elevated, Hypertension Stage 1, and Hypertension Stage 2)

Once of the downsides of this data is the already binned variables i.e.cholesterol, glucose, and Bp_Category which led this researcher to avoid binning any further variables to limit the amount of binned variables. We have to rely on whomever compiled this data and assigned the categories to each patients levels and this researcher was unable to determine what levels these categories were based on. While, binning is a very powerful method for ease of interpretation of the output and helps with reducing the sensitivity to outliers it can also lead to overfitting the data and loss of details in the relationships of the data.

2 Methodology

Linear and logistic regression were the two main methodologies employed in this comprehensive analysis of cardiovascular data. This section provides an overview of these methodologies highlighting their objectives and structural components.

2.1 Linear Regression

Linear regression is a statistical technique used to model the relationship between a continuous dependent variable and predictor variable(s). Linear regression will subsequently be applied to examine which predictor variable(s) are statistically significant in predicting BMI. Additionally, the significant variables will lend insight into their relationship with BMI whether that being a positive or negative correlation.

The structural form of a linear regression model is given by:

\(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \epsilon\).

These components of linear regression consist of:

  • \(Y_i\) denotes the outcome (or response) variable for subject \(i\).
  • \(X_{1i}\) denotes the predictor of interest (\(X_1\)) for subject \(i\).
  • \(\beta_0\) denotes the Y-intercept when \(X\) is zero.
  • \(\beta_1\) denotes the slope or the change in \(Y\) with a 1-unit change in \(X\).
  • \(\epsilon\) denotes the error or residuals.

The subsequent analysis aims to identify the key predictors of BMI and explore their corresponding effects.

2.2 Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is a statistical technique used for modeling the probability of a binary outcome. Well use this technique in the subsequent analysis to assess the impact of various variables such as: BMI, age, cholesterol levels, smoking status, and etc. on the likelihood of having cardiovascular disease represented by our dependent variable CardioDisease.

The logistic regression model allows us to estimate the odds of an outcome occuring via the logistic function in R by way of converting a linear relationship into a probability. The probability of this event allows us to predict, in this case whether a person will have cardiovascular disease or not.

The structural form of a logistic regression model is given by:

\(logit(p) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 +\beta_kX_k\).

These components of logistic regression consist of:

  • \(logit(p)\) is the log-odds of the probability of an event occurring.
  • \(\beta_0\) denotes the Y-intercept when \(X\) is zero.
  • \(\beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_k\) are the coefficients associated with the explanatory variables
  • \(X_1, X_2, X_k\) are the explanatory variables

Both strategies for the analysis will serve important purposes in assisting to uncover significant relationships between our predictor and response variables whether they be quantitative for linear regression or categorical for logistic regression

3.1 Handling Missing Value

We can see below there are no missing values in the Cardio dataset which is also presented later on in the analysis via the summary function of the dataset.

Missing_Values <- Cardio[apply(is.na(Cardio), 1, any), ]
print(Missing_Values)
 [1] ID            Age           Height        Weight        Systolic_BP  
 [6] Diastolic_BP  BMI           Age_Years     Gender        Cholesterol  
[11] Glucose       Smoke         Alcohol       Active        CardioDisease
[16] Bp_Category  
<0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)

However, if this dataset should contain missing values, and they were missing at random we would want to impute these values. I would use KNN (K Nearest Neighbors) which is a strong method that utilizes how close observations are known as euclidean distances to help predict what the missing value would be given the known value of observations closest neighbors. Whether it being the mean or median of the closest neighbors for a numerical value or the majority of nearest neighbors for categorical missing values. One thing to keep in mind though is we would want to normalize our data as to not give too much influence to any one variable when performing such processes.

3.2.1 Data Cleaning

While removing observations is not always the preferred approach, there seems to be some errors in the data collected as mentioned earlier and viewed in the visual representations of the boxplots and density curves. The robustness of our dataset will allow for the removal observations that were certain are errors without impacting the accuracy of our analysis. The Min and Max BMI recorded in the dataset is 3.472 & 298.667 respectively. The BMI cut off points for the World Health Organization (WHO) are defined as a person is Severely Underweight: <16 kg/m2 and Morbidly Obese: 40.0 kg/m2 (Zierle-Ghosh and Jan 2023) making these min and max values physically impossible raising concerns about the reliability of the dataset. Since BMI is calculated via height and weight, there is a large range of BMI values a person could reasonably have. Therefore, observations where BMI values were less than 15 and greater than 80 (2x high end) were removed from the dataset. The removal of these observations resulted in 56 observations being removed. Additionally since were working with an adult dataset, any observations with a height of less 140cm was removed resulting in a new dataset named NewCardio consisting of 68,033 observations. The removal of these 172 observations are inconsequential in terms of the robustness of our data and if given more access to the dataset a proper investigation would be conducted to verify the data entry was conducted correctly.

There are several variables that are already binned in the dataset i.e.Cholesterol, Glucose, active, and BP_Category as these are variable classifications dependent on numeric readouts. A downside of this dataset is were unable to determine what levels these categories were binned into. The variable active does not allow us to know what level of activity these patients had whether it was measured on a per week basis or some other metric. We would like to avoid binning more variables as were already limited to accessibility of the raw data values in this binned variables. Therefore, we took a look at skewness of the variables BMI (although will not be used), height, Weight, Combined_BP, and Age_years to see if any transformations are necessary. We can see below that Weight (0.9941015) and BMI (1.19436) are heavily skewed to the right as stated previously looking at the density curves.

Since we will not be utilizing the variable BMI in our analysis as it is a calculation of Height and Weight and could introduce collinearity, we performed a log transformation on only the weight variable.

The data failed the shapiro-Wilkes test for normality even after performing a box-cox transformation on the continuous data. A decision was made to move forward with only transforming the weight variable to Log_Weight for ease of interpretability and given the fact we know there were data errors in the original dataset we will interpret the results with significant scrutiny. A in-depth look into the data gathering process for this dataset would need to be conducted if we hoped to utilize it in a clinical or research setting.

library(moments)
skewness_weight <- skewness(NewCardio$Weight, na.rm = TRUE)
skewness_height <- skewness(NewCardio$Height, na.rm = TRUE)
skewness_age_years <- skewness(NewCardio$Age_Years, na.rm = TRUE)
skewness_bmi <- skewness(NewCardio$BMI, na.rm = TRUE)

3.3 Accessing Pairwise Plots

We see in the pairwise plots that BMI and Weight have a strong correlation which is expected given that BMI is calculated from height and weight. The decision was made to drop the variable BMI from subsequent analysis due to its strong positive correlation with weight of 0.868 posing a risk for multi-collinearity. Also due to the fact it is a calculation of height and weight. Were also more interested in the weight of the patient as it give a better overall picture of a persons physical characteristics instead of keeping just BMI and dropping height and weight. We also see as expected that height and BMI are negatively correlated where as height increases BMI decreases. A less strong positive correlation is that of systolic and diastolic BP with BMI being nearly the same at 0.268 & 0.240 respectively. We also see a weak positive correlation as Age_Years increase as does BMI.

4 Statistical Regression Modeling

4.1 Linear Regression Modeling

4.1.1 Statement of the Question(s)

Our objective for building a linear regression model was to address the question: What explanatory variables are significant in predicting a patients Log_Weight and what is the relationship between our explanatory variables and the response variable Log_Weight? In order words, which variables are significant in helping us determine a patients weight. The purpose of the subsequent analysis conducted focused on association and subsequent prediction.

4.1.2 Data Justification

Our justification of utilizing this dataset is very solid as our sample size is Very robust with 68,033 observations and no missing values. The dataset includes both continuous variables and categorical variables set up as factors with levels. The response variable Log_Weight is a continuous variable for which we have done a transformation on it to reduce the skewness of the distribution. Additionally, We observed correlations between the continuous variables and Weight therefore supporting the use of linear regression.Since our data contains continuous and categorical variables, this will enhance the models explanatory power giving us a stronger model to provide predictions of Log_Weight if given explanatory inputs.

Given the aforementioned points regarding the data, we believe there is ample justification for using a linear regression model to model the relationship between Log_Weight and selected explanatory variables.

Below we see the 3 model summaries, and we will focus on the stepwise selection for reasons detailed further in the analysis. We see there are many statistically significant explanatory variables involved in determining the weight of a patient, even taking into the other explanatory variables in the model. We see that all the regression coefficients are positive except those of Active where the patient was physically active and gender where the patient was male. This shows us a negative correlation between Weight and activity level, as well as weight and male patients. We see that for every 1 unit increase in GlucoseAboveNormal the corresponding Log_Weight increases on average by 0.0482311. Whereas, for every 1 unit increase in GlucoseHigh the patients Log_Weight only increases by 0.0155445. Perhaps, those patients who have very high glucose may be diabetic and are more mindful of their weight resulting in a less increase in Weight.

The resulting Linear Model Regression equation:

\(LogWeight = 2.5261843 + 0.0038556*Combined BP + 0.0005779*AgeYears + 0.0234864*CholesterAboveNormal + 0.0462264*CholesterolHigh \\ + 0.0482311*GlucoseAboveNormal +0.0155445*GlucoseHigh - 0.0060168*ActiveActive - 0.0103789*GenderMale + 0.0081468*Height + \epsilon\).

4.3 Logistic Regression Modeling

As stated previously in the linear regression modeling our data is very well suited for logistic regression modelling as well. We first fit the initial regression model with CardioDisease as the response variable and all the predictor variables in the dataset minus BMI, systolic and diastolic BP since Weight, Height, and Bp_category encompass those variables to avoid multicollinearity.

We see in the summary of the significant tests that gender and having a glucose of above normal is not significant at the 0.05 level. While it looks like Bp_CategoryHypertension Stage 2, Log_Weight, and CholesterolHigh all have the highest regression coefficients increasing the log odds of a positive (CardioDisease Yes) event the most. We also see numerous negative relationships indicating they reduce the log odds.

Logistic_Model <- glm(CardioDisease ~ Bp_Category + Age_Years + Height + Log_Weight + Gender + Cholesterol + Glucose + 
  Smoke + Alcohol + Active, 
  family = binomial,data = NewCardio)

The reduced model will include the practically important variables considered for this analysis albeit most of the variables in the dataset could make an argument to be included will be limited to Bp_Category, Age_years, Cholesterol, and Log_Weight. Active, Smoke, and alcohol were not selected as we are not privy to knowing the values for the patients for these variables and are reliant on the binned variables. We performed the analysis using the both functionality for direction which is essentially the same as stepwise for linear regression. The result is very similar to the initial model minus removing gender as not significant.

The resulting Logistic Model Regression equation:

\(Logit(p) = -7.9157441 + 0.4208538*BpCategory Hypertension 1 + 1.8885847*BpCategory Hypertension 2 - 0.3774414*BpCategoryNormal + \\ 0.0579817*AgeYears - 0.0078703*Height + 1.2832004*LogWeight + 0.4349982*CholesterolAboveNormal + 1.1961829*CholesterolHigh \\ + 0.0350072*GlucoseAboveNormal - 0.3604139*GlucoseHigh - 0.1030532*SmokerSmoker - 0.1949753*AlcoholConsumesalcohol - 0.2235626*ActiveActive\)

reduced.model <- glm(CardioDisease ~ Bp_Category + Age_Years + Cholesterol + Log_Weight, family = binomial, data = NewCardio)

final.model <- step(Logistic_Model, scope = list(lower = formula(reduced.model),  upper = formula(Logistic_Model)), data = NewCardio, 
direction = "both", trace = 0)

We can see below inputting 4 new observations into the dataset allows us to see what the predicted outcome will be at the cut off probability of 0.5. mynewdata <- data.frame(
  Bp_Category = factor(c("Hypertension Stage 1", "Normal", "Hypertension Stage 2", "Elevated"),
                       levels = c("Elevated", "Hypertension Stage 1", "Hypertension Stage 2", "Normal")),
  Age_Years = c(45, 30, 55, 60),

                       levels = c("Normal", "Above Normal", "High")),
  Glucose = factor(c("Normal", "Above Normal", "Normal", "Above Normal"),
                   levels = c("Normal", "Above Normal")),
  Smoke = factor(c("Smoker", "Non-smoker", "Smoker", "Smoker"),
                 levels = c("Non-smoker", "Smoker")),
  Alcohol = factor(c("Consumes alcohol", "No alcohol", "Consumes alcohol", "Consumes alcohol"),

                  levels = c("Active", "Not Active")))

4.4 Results and Conclusion

The results from this in-depth analsysis shows us there are many variables that influence a persons status of whether they have a cardiovascular disease. Perhaps, this is one of the reason that just general overall health is the best medicine as there are numerous variables that can result in increasing a patients probability. On the other hand, the linear model for the Log_Weight didnt yield as promising results as the logistic model did. We were only able to model ~20% of the variance of the Log_Weight variable. I believe this is due to there are many other variables and factors in a patients life that has more influence on their weight. We did see however note that patients without cardiovasculars diseases on average weighed less than those with cardiovascular diseases. The variables in this dataset were better put to use looking at the intended response variable of CardioDisease. We still did see some meaningful results where we confirmed a widely known fact that being active has a negative correlation with ones weight and that factors such as having high cholsterol and high glucose are positively correlated indicating indicating that as they increase we would expect the patients weight on average to increase as well by way of the regression coefficients identified in the model.

5 Summary and Discussion

There are multiple limitations to this dataset, some of which was already discussed in this analysis. The main issue with this dataset is the overall in-depth knowledge of the variables and how the data was obtained is lacking. The type of cardiovascular disease is not identified as there are numerous different cardiovascular diseases. The question is, did all the patients have the same cardiovascular disease or were they all grouped into one? The lumping all patients into one cardiovascular disease group would be very irresponsible if we were to hope to provide valuable defensible statistical analysis for the predictors of cardiovascular disease as not every disease is the same.

The amount of physical activity is ambiguous as we dont know the metrics that were used to classify each patient and whether it was observed or simply a questionnaire which can be very unreliable means of obtaining data for such a variable. Many people tend to exaggerate characteristics that are seen to be good and underestimate those that are perceived to be bad when given a survey response type of question leading to unreliable data points.

While there were many issues with this dataset, I do believe it is a good starting place to start to look at the overall general idea of how these types of variables affect cardiac health. We would need more descriptive and more refined variables if we were to hope to elicit very meaningful clinical results here. These would be my suggestions to the researcher who compiled this dataset as to not generalize the data as much as they did and to provide values of the raw data and how it was binned in order to get a better understanding of the origin of the data. We noted in the beginning there were some physically impossible values therefore, a view of the raw data values would be best to take any next steps with this data.
